{
  "text": "A light microscope with a crossed micrometer was used to examine every section of each fragment of cortical tissue. Using a slightly modified version of the system employed by [CITATION_1] follicles were classified according to their developmental stage dependent on the morphology and abundance of the granulosa cells observed as follows: (i) non-growing follicles: follicles constituting the resting pool, characterized by oocytes surrounded by a complete or incomplete single layer of cells, either all flat (primordial) or a mixed layer of flattened and cuboidal cells (transitory) [CITATION_2] , (ii) primary follicles: follicles comprising of an oocyte surrounded by a single layer of cuboidal granulosa cells, (iii) secondary follicles: multilaminar follicles with more than a single layer of cuboidal granulosa cells and (iv) antral: antrum present within a multilaminar follicle. Evaluation of isolated follicles and follicles within cortical fragments was made on the section containing the nucleolus except when determining the presence of an antrum in isolated follicles where all sections of the follicle were examined. Mean follicle and oocyte diameter was recorded for each isolated and fragment-enclosed follicle evaluated.",
